<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="0c66524d-5bfd-59f3-a680-d7e650fdefab" activityNameId="f32c2cb0-89e1-4dc5-8534-dfe6bffc5e7f" parentActivityId="d5672b7c-70d5-5dc6-ab73-b31998d36272" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">copper oxide production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Banacobru ol</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Copper monoxide</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Copper oxide (CuO)</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">CUPRIC OXIDE</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Oxocopper</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Copper(II) oxide</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity includes the consumption of raw materials and chemicals used for production, the estimated emissions to air and water, as well as the energy consumption and infrastructure use. Solid wastes are omitted.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of solid copper(II)oxide (CuO) by hydrometallurgy. Copper oxide occurs in nature as the black minerals tenorite and paramelaconite. Copper oxide is mostly used in the production of compounds for wood preservation and is also used as a precursor of a variety of copper (II) salts. Further areas of use or application are the feed industry (additives) and the glass and ceramic industry (pigment). (Zhang and Richardson 2016)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Due to a lack of data, this dataset is based on stoechiometric calculations as well as approximations based on data from a large chemical plant (Gendorf 2016).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. Final report ecoinvent data v2.0 No. 8. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Zhang, J. and Richardson, H. W. 2016. Copper Compounds. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. 1–31.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The data used has no specific geographical origin as it is based on stoechiometric calculations and estimations. It is assumed to be representative of the production processes in this geography. Some values are based on data from a large chemical factory located in Germany. These are assumed to be valid for this geography.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">According to Zhang and Richardson (2016), the most common production method for copper(II) oxide is the use of hydrometallurgy. In this process, a solution of ammonia and ammonium carbonate leaches metallic copper in the presence of air. The leaching step involves three reaction steps, of which the first one is very slow compared to the following two steps. Therefore, only a continuous operation of the plant achieves good results. After the leaching step, several filtering and stripping steps are carried out before the copper(II) oxide can be dryied and packed. The used ammonia and carbon dioxide are recovered in the strip tank and go back to the starting point.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The overall reaction of the hydrometallurgical production of copper(II)oxide can be summarized out of the following two reaction steps (leaching and stripping):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">4 Cu + O2 + 4 NH3 + 2 (NH4)2CO3 → 2 Cu2(NH3)4CO3 + 2 H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">2 Cu2(NH3)4CO3 + O2 → 4 CuO + 8 NH3 + 2 CO2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">The overall process yield is assumed to be 98%. The inventory is based on stoechiometric calculations. The emissions to air (0.2 wt% of raw material input) and water were estimated using mass balance. Treatment of the waste water in an internal waste water treatment plant assumed (elimination efficiency of 90% for C).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Reference:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Zhang, J. and Richardson, H. W. 2016. Copper Compounds. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. 1–31.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2000-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Date of published literature. Some values are based on data published by the Gendorf factory that were collected between 2011 and 2015. The time period has been adjusted accordingly. For more details, see the comments of the exchanges.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
